SIMPLE: lurch
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lurch
<hw>Lurch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>lurcare</ets>, <ets>lurcari</ets>.]</ety> <def>To swallow or eat
greedily; to devour; hence, to swallow up.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Too far off from great cities, which may hinder business; too near
them, which <qex>lurcheth</qex> all provisions, and maketh everything
dear.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lurch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lurch
<hw>Lurch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>lourche</ets> name of a
game; as adj., deceived, embarrassed.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An old
game played with dice and counters; a variety of the game of
tables.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A double score in cribbage for the winner when his
adversary has been left in the <xex>lurch</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lady --- has cried her eyes out on losing a <qex>lurch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To leave one in the lurch</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In
the game of cribbage, to leave one's adversary so far behind that the
game is won before he has scored thirty-one.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
leave one behind; hence, to abandon, or fail to stand by, a person in a
difficulty.</cd> <au>Denham.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But though thou'rt of a different church,⟦br⟧
I will not <qex>leave thee in the lurch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Lurch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lurch
<hw>Lurch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To leave in the lurch;
to cheat.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never deceive or <qex>lurch</qex> the sincere communicant.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To steal; to rob.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in the brunt of seventeen battles since⟦br⟧
He <qex>lurched</qex> all swords of the garland.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lurch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Lurch
<hw>Lurch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. W. <ets>llerch</ets>,
<ets>llerc</ets>, a frisk, a frisking backward or forward, a loitering,
a lurking, a lurking, <ets>llercian</ets>, <ets>llerciaw</ets>, to be
idle, to frisk; or perh. fr. E. <ets>lurch</ets> to lurk.]</ety> <def>A
sudden roll of a ship to one side, as in heavy weather; hence, a swaying
or staggering movement to one side, as that by a drunken man.</def>
<mark>Fig.</mark>: <def>A sudden and capricious inclination of the
mind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 876 --></p>

<p><ent>Lurch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Lurch
<hw>Lurch</hw> <pr>(l⟦ucir⟧rch)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lurched</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦ucir⟧rcht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lurching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To roll or sway suddenly to one
side, as a ship or a drunken man; to move forward while
lurching.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lurch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Lurch
<hw>Lurch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[A variant of
<ets>lurk</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To withdraw to one side, or to
a private place; to lurk.</def> <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dodge; to shift; to play tricks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I . . . am fain to shuffle, to hedge, and to <qex>lurch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lurcher</ent>⟦br⟧
